english:
  title: Inscription on the Hall of Circularity, with Preface
  author: Jung Chu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Formless One took his name from being born of the formless—thus did the gentleman Jeong of Seowon, bearing the surname Gwon, style himself so. He named his dwelling the Hall of Circularity.

    Someone offered praise, saying: "Heaven, by virtue of its circular form, revolves eternally, birthing all things without cease. The sun, by virtue of its circular form, travels its course, completing the year in endless succession. How vast is the meaning of circularity!"

    Formless One laughed and replied: "Do you seek to flatter me? All things are born from the formless, yet become bound by form. Bound by form, transformation grows difficult. When transformation grows difficult, the principle becomes obscured. I, however, take my stand in the formless and honor its capacity for change. What I call circularity is this: to be without blockage, without obstruction—this alone is precious. But what you praise is merely the round shape of heaven and sun. How can such things warrant reverence? Yet it is true—where form exists, principle exists. But should we divide them in two and abandon form to seek principle alone, how could we truly call it circular? Your words have stirred my mind. It is fitting that I inscribe this teaching beside my seat."

    Thus he composed this inscription:

    *A vessel with angular edges easily becomes chipped.*
    *A wheel's circumference—what path can it not traverse?*
    *Should I learn to be circular, refusing to cling to any corner,*
    *What treacherous road need I fear to walk?*
  footnotes:
    - Formless One (無形子) is a philosophical title adopted by the author, reflecting Daoist and Neo-Confucian thought about the relationship between the formless and the formed.
    - The preface employs the classical Chinese literary device of recording both praise and the subject's witty response, which serves as a philosophical dialogue.
    - 'The final inscription employs extended metaphor: the chipped vessel represents rigidity and limitation, while the wheel''s wholeness represents adaptability and universal accessibility.'
